statement:
Let

\begin{align*}A = \left(\begin{array}{cc}
3 & 1 \\ -4 & -1
\end{array}\right)\end{align*}

\textbf{(b)} Find the general solution of the system of equations

\begin{align*}\mathbf{x}' = A\mathbf{x}\end{align*}

Here
$\mathbf{x}(t) = \left(\begin{array}{c} x_1(t) \\Â x_2(t) \end{array}\right)$

sols:
\_\_NOTOC\_\_

To begin with we matrix \emph{M} in Jordan normal form, such that
\emph{A = SMS\textsuperscript{-1}}. To do we need to find the
(generalized) eigenvector of \emph{A}.

\subparagraph{Eigenvector \emph{v}}\label{eigenvector-v}

Knowing $\lambda = 1$, we will proceed to find our eigenvectors by
solving $(A - \lambda I)v = 0$.

$\left(\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 1 \\ -4 & -2
\end{array}\right) \left(\begin{array}{c}
v_1 \\ v_2
\end{array}\right) = \left(\begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 0
\end{array}\right)$

which gives the homogeneous system

$\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 1 \\ -4 & -2
\end{array}\right]$.

Placing this in reduced-row form we get

\begin{align*}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 1 \\ 0 & 0
\end{array}\right]\end{align*}

so that $v_2 = -2 v_1$. We take

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}v = (1, -2)^T\end{align*}

as the eigenvector.

Unfortunately, we only find one eigenvector from this, and we'll need to
consider generalized eigenvectors and the Jordan canonical form in order
to solve this problem.

\subparagraph{Find the generalized eigenvector
\emph{w}}\label{find-the-generalized-eigenvector-w}

The generalized eigenvector satisfies $(A - \lambda I)w = v$ which gives
us

$\left(\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 1 \\ -4 & -2
\end{array}\right) \left(\begin{array}{c}
w_1 \\ w_2
\end{array}\right) = \left(\begin{array}{c}
1 \\ -2
\end{array}\right).$

Row reductions lead to

$\left(\begin{array}{cc}
2 & 1 \\ 0 & 0
\end{array}\right) \left(\begin{array}{c}
w_1 \\ w_2
\end{array}\right) = \left(\begin{array}{c}
1 \\ 0
\end{array}\right)$

which has a solution set that can be parameterized by $w_1$:

\begin{align*}\left(\begin{array}{c}
w_1 \\ 1 - 2w_1
\end{array}\right) = w_1 \left(\begin{array}{c}
1 \\ -2
\end{array}\right) + \left(\begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 1
\end{array}\right).\end{align*}

For simplicity, we can take $w_1 = 0$ so that our generalized
eigenvector is

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}w = (0,1)^T.\end{align*}

\subparagraph{Setting up the Jordan normal form
\emph{M}}\label{setting-up-the-jordan-normal-form-m}

Having found the generalized eigenvector, we get that the matrix A has
Jordan Canonical form

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}A = SMS^{-1}\end{align*}

where

\begin{align*}S = \left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0 \\ -2 & 1
\end{array}\right)\end{align*} is the matrix with columns being the eigenvectors,
and

\begin{align*}M = \left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1 \\ 0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\end{align*} is the matrix with the eigenvalues along the
diagonal with 1's above them.

A quick computation yields

\begin{align*}S^{-1} = \left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0 \\ 2 & 1
\end{array}\right).\end{align*}

Our system states that

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x' = A x\end{align*}

where

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}x = (x_1, x_2)^T.\end{align*}

We can therefore write,

\begin{align*}
x' &= SMS^{-1} x\\
S^{-1} x' &= M S^{-1} x\\
y' &= M y\end{align*}

where

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y = S^{-1} x.\end{align*}

\subparagraph{Solve the simplified system \emph{y' =
My}}\label{solve-the-simplified-system-y-my}

The system

\begin{align*}y' = My=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 1 \\ 0 & 1
\end{array}\right)\begin{pmatrix}y_1\\y_2\end{pmatrix}\end{align*}

tells us

\begin{align*} y_1' &= y_1 + y_2 \\ y_2' &= y_2 \end{align*}.

The second equation gives us

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}y_2 = c e^t.\end{align*}

Using this in the first equation means

\begin{align*}
y_1' &= y_1 + c e^t\\
y_1' - y_1 &= c e^t\\
e^{-t}y_1' - e^{-t}y_1 &= (e^{-t} y_1)' = c\\
e^{-t}y_1 &= ct + b\\
y_1 &= (ct + b) e^t \end{align*}

which has been solved using integrating factors. Now we have

\begin{align*}y = \left(\begin{array}{c}
ct e^t + b e^t \\ c e^t
\end{array}\right)\end{align*}

\subparagraph{Recover the solution
\emph{x}}\label{recover-the-solution-x}

which immediately gives us our solution x,

$x = Sy = \left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0 \\ -2 & 1
\end{array}\right) \left(\begin{array}{c}
ct e^t + b e^t \\ c e^t
\end{array}\right) = \left(\begin{array}{c}
ct e^t + b e^t \\ -2 c t e^t + (c-2b) e^t
\end{array}\right)$.

